SIMPLE: funnel
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Funnel
<hw>Fun"nel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>funel</ets>,
<ets>fonel</ets>, prob. through OF. fr, L. <ets>fundibulum</ets>,
<ets>infundibulum</ets>, funnel, fr. <ets>infundere</ets> to pour in; in
in + <ets>fundere</ets> to pour; cf. Armor. <ets>founil</ets> funnel, W.
<ets>ffynel</ets> air hole, chimney. See <er>Fuse</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A vessel of the shape of an inverted
hollow cone, terminating below in a pipe, and used for conveying liquids
or pourable solids into a vessel with a narrow opening; a
tunnel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A passage or avenue for a fluid or flowing
substance; specifically, a smoke flue or pipe; the iron chimney of a
steamship or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Funnel box</b></col> <fld>(Mining)</fld>, <cd>an
apparatus for collecting finely crushed ore from water.</cd>
<au>Knight.</au> -- <col><b>Funnel stay</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>one of the ropes or rods steadying a steamer's funnel.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Funnelform</ent>⟦br⟧
